data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 and require **no migration**.

That said, for .NET 8 I'd recommend modernizing from raw `Thread` to `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you better thread-pool utilization and natural support for `CancellationToken` if you need cancellation later — which is the cooperative replacement for `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
